<TITLE> Dalit Meira Kumar elected India's first woman Speaker </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 3 (bdnews24.com)Sixty four-year-old Meira Kumar, unanimously elected Speaker of the Indian parliament on Wednesday, made a double entry into the history books as the first woman and the first Dalit to hold one of the highest Constitutional posts. Congress party's Kumar was elected by a voice vote amidst thumping of desks by the entire House, following a resolution by ruling United Progressive Alliance chief Sonia Gandhi and seconded by Leader of the House Pranab Mukherjee. A former foreign service official and Union Minister, she was elected to the Lok Sabha from Sasaram in Bihar in the recent elections. Follwing Wednesday's vote, Prime Minister Manmohan Singh escorted Kumar, who was sitting in the front benches, to the Speaker's chair. Singh, celebrating her election as a historic one, said her services as a diplomat, 25 years as a parliamentarian and her role as a minister would stand her in good stead for her new job. Leaders cutting across the political spectrum, including L K Advani (BJP, Mamata Banerjee (Trinamool Congress), T R Baalu (DMK), Arjun Charan Sethi BJD), Sharad Yadav (JD-U), Mulayam Singh Yadav (SP), Lalu Prasad (RJD), Ram Sundar Das (JD-U), Sharad Pawar (NCP), Farooq Abdullah (NC) and E Ahmed (Muslim League) had also tabled their motions proposing Kumar for the post
